  "prompt": "How can you determine the derivative of [math]\\sin x^2[/math]?",
  "response": "To determine the derivative of [math]\\(\\sin(x^2)\\)[/math], we'll use the **chain rule** from calculus. The chain rule is employed when differentiating a composition of functions.\n\n### Step-by-Step Solution:\n\n1. **Identify the Inner and Outer Functions:**\n   \n   - **Inner Function:** [math]\\(u = x^2\\)[/math]\n   - **Outer Function:** [math]\\(\\sin(u)\\)[/math]\n\n2. **Differentiate the Outer Function with Respect to [math]\\(u\\)[/math]:**\n   \n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{du} [\\sin(u)] = \\cos(u)\n   \\]\n\n3. **Differentiate the Inner Function with Respect to [math]\\(x\\)[/math]:**\n   \n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{dx} [x^2] = 2x\n   \\]\n\n4. **Apply the Chain Rule:**\n   \n   The chain rule states that if [math]\\(y = \\sin(u)\\)[/math] and [math]\\(u = x^2\\)[/math], then:\n   \n   \\[\n   \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{dy}{du} \\cdot \\frac{du}{dx}\n   \\]\n   \n   Substituting the derivatives from steps 2 and 3:\n   \n   \\[\n   \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\cos(u) \\cdot 2x\n   \\]\n   \n5. **Substitute Back [math]\\(u = x^2\\)[/math]:**\n   \n   \\[\n   \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\cos(x^2) \\cdot 2x\n   \\]\n\n### Final Answer:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dx} [\\sin(x^2)] = 2x \\cos(x^2)\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{2x \\cos(x^2)}\n\\]",
